segments.text: I will have my outer office packed with those students whose names are in that little box and I need to see those students face to face individually and what I do with them then I say let me see your schedule let me see why you have to have this course and I try to substitute a course now this is after Donna Wiseman and Dave Armstrong have worked with these kids initially so you can see we have some layers but

It gets to the point where I have to say, I'm sorry, I think that you'll need to take this course in the fall and try to find a substitute course because you're not going to be student teaching until the fall of 89.
And isn't that adding another incredible burden to you right now, not knowing the outcome of this decision?
I mean, how can you make those decisions without even knowing what kind of program you're going to have?
We know our present program will be in place until 1991.
And all of our students who came in in the fall must be graduated by 1991 under the old, under the present program.
If they are not, they won't be able to be certified.
What was I hearing about, you know, we have to have something by January because this new thing is going to have to be implemented in September?
We have to have something in place by January.
in order to get it through the university curriculum committees and be approved so we can have a new program in place by September.
For the ones that are coming in in 88?
Exactly.
Because, you see, they will be the graduating class of 92.
So our department will not only have the management problems we presently face, but we are going to be serving two programs at one time
for the next three years.
And this will be just your department, pretty much, won't it?
I mean, it'll affect this one the majority.
It'll affect, for example, educational psychology would be affected by those service courses that they have in our program.
But our department is the greatest affected.
And we all have dual programs going on.
What has this done to the climate in your department as far as teacher morale or anxiety or the unknown?
The fear of the unknown, I guess, is the worst.
How do you deal with that as a department head and manager?
How do you manage the people?
Well, that's part of the management problem.
I think that if you're perceived as trying to maintain
a class load that is appropriate.
For example, the time I spend with these kids who need to get into classes, I do not add a student to a class except in an emergency, unless a faculty member has signed a form accepting the student.
Now let me explain that.
If you came to me and you said you wanted to get into

a class and it was closed I would say here is a form and you need to take this to Professor Alexander and her class is closed and if she signs her name on this accepting you into that class then I will admit you so Pat Alexander has made the decision that she will take that 31st student into her class then I put that person in now for those faculty
who are too soft-hearted, I sometimes have to stop and say, you know, even the form isn't going to do.
We simply can't.
The instruction is going to be affected.
So that I think in that way, the faculty understands that I'm just not sitting here and adding 47 kids to your class.
It's their decision first.
And if there's an emergency, then I may call and say, Pat, we have a student who's doing student teaching next semester.
Yours is the only class.
Is there any possibility we can get her in?
And so I might do a face-to-face or a telephone conversation with a faculty member.
Then that kind of leads me into all these changes and all the things that are happening are going to impact, obviously, the future and what the College of Education will be in the 21st century.
And I see that you had some notes in there.
Do you have a crystal ball to what you feel like?
I think we've covered most of these.
But let me share with you, first of all,
One of the changes that I feel very positive about in regard to the institution, and that is the special effort that is being made for the recruitment of minorities.
And I'm very, I'm going to be very point about that, I'm very proud of the fact that we now have in place
an English as a second language teacher preparation program.
Dean came here in 1980, I came here in 1981.
I knew something about Texas and I knew something about the makeup of Texas.
And so I was quite surprised, I'd say relatively surprised, that when I came here we did not have any program in the department that addressed the needs of the minorities in the state of Texas.
The first individual that was recruited in this department was Dr. .
And she was recruited to develop a program in ESL bilingual education.
She has done a superb job in that regard.
And she's another individual.
She got the Outstanding New Faculty Award, and this year she got the Teaching Award.
And do you know that she has submitted 13 proposals in the short time she has been here?
And has a number of those, I think eight of those were funded.
We are now, we have Dr. Gracilia Pena Rosenberg, who will be coming to us in January to help us in our bilingual program.
We've gotten that program off the ground.
We had very few women in our department.
We now have
added women to our program.
We have two black females.

And we've added, I guess what I'm saying is that I feel very proud of the fact that we are addressing the kinds of needs that I think Texas has had for a long time in teacher preparation, and that is role models.
And I think the institution is moving in that direction.
And I'm very pleased with that.
We have a minority mentorship program that we have just developed for our undergraduate teacher preparation program.
And Dr. Patricia Lark, who is our minority, and Dr. Donna Wiseman have put this program together.
And what that program entails is that we have enlisted the help of minority community leaders in the Bryan College Station area
to help us screen about 30 elementary education majors into this program.
And these elementary education majors will be serving as mentors to the same number of elementary students in Bryan College Station who are in the sixth, seventh, and eighth grades.
They will be
These students have been identified by these community leaders as having parental support for education and academic promise.

And what we hope will happen is that our mentors, by working with them, will help them to achieve academic success in the sixth, seventh, and eighth grades, which will build them a foundation for having success in high school, which will bring them into the university level.
And at the same time, it's going to sensitize our 30 elementary education majors to working in a multicultural classroom.
I'm very proud of that program.
Would you be willing to share that model?
Because in my new job with this office in San Antonio, that's what I'm going to be doing is working with the 6th, 7th, and 8th graders.
And that could be a wonderful launching thing.
And we might be able to expand it.
OK. Sure.
Dr. Lahr.
OK. Dr. Weitzman.
Great.
That would be wonderful.
That's one of the things that I'm very proud of.
I think another area that I'm very proud of, when I came here, we had one computer and one Diablo printer in this department.
Wow.
Every faculty member now has a computer in his or her office.
Every secretary is computerized, has a computer.
We are on a SIMS, obviously the SIMS, which the university now has moved to computerizing their registration and so forth.
We have a laser printer.
We have a, our curriculum and our instructional research lab have computers in them.
What I'm particularly proud of is that we are on the cutting edge of technology in this department so that we are going to be moving to a new configuration
in terms of our support staff and how it will be functioning in relation to our faculty needs that will bring our technology to play at the highest level of the state of art.
And we're going to be doing that probably within the next year.
How did you accomplish all this?
With the help of the faculty, with the fact of using our resources wisely.
And that's what I'm saying was a management type of thing.
procedure that we went through.
So I'm kind of proud of that, too.
That was one of the other aspects.
And I spoke about recruitment of minorities.
So what do I see for the 21st century?
Well, I think I see something not too dissimilar from some ideas that I put forward.
I had an article that I was invited to write for my specialty is English education.
And an organization I belong to
called Conference on English Education.
And they had two journals that they devoted to invited articles, and one journal was on needed research.
And they asked me to write an article in that regard.
And one of the things I said was that I believed that in the very near future, one of the things that we would be doing in teacher education is to try to prepare
teacher scholars who are also researchers.
In other words, teacher researchers.
And I believe that we are just on the horizon of doing that at Susannan University.
And it's right in keeping with the Holmes Group agenda in terms of major research institutions becoming involved in teacher education.
That's why I'm so proud of that.
I'll take a copy of that article.

And I think what's going to happen is that we're going to have much more collaboration of our faculty with public school teachers in the area of classroom research so that it's out there where it's taking place.
And I think that we're going to find that our whole thrust will be in producing
these teacher scholars who are also researchers, and that our faculty are going to build that research base that our teachers may not have.
But the two of them together, with the practical experience of a teacher coupled with the research expertise of our faculty, could do wonders.
Just do wonders.
I think I see that on our horizon.
So you're not apprehensive about this new program that is about to come about?
You think that it has a positive?
I mean, everybody's sold.
I think we have an opportunity.
I think I'm optimistic about it.
And are you able to project that to your faculty?
I think to some degree.
I would be less than honest if I didn't tell you that there are some faculty that are reticent about what's happening.
They're not certain that we have proven that one thing is better than another.
My feeling is we could go on for years and never have proof.
We have to move forward.
I think the climate now, the educational reform is saying, as parents were saying, we expect our teachers to be fully prepared and to be scholars.
and to be able to not only make a diagnosis, but be able to make a remediation if that's necessary.
And you can't do that unless you have a scholar researcher.
Do you think, though, that it's going to affect teacher shortage?
I mean, we already have a teacher shortage, but is that going to make it worse?
In other words, prevent people from going into teaching because they feel like it's, you know, five years and then you come out and you're not making as much as...
That's what I'm hearing from a lot of people.
How do you respond to that?
Because I'm having trouble responding.
I'm going to say this, and I hope it's taken the right way.
I mentioned earlier about my career being spent in major research institutions.
And I believe Texas A&M University is such an institution.
And I believe teacher education is part of that research agenda.
And our role is to produce the educational leaders of tomorrow.
If it has some effect on the numbers that we are able to produce,

then I say that must be balanced by the even higher quality of individual we will be putting out who will go out there and work with those people who didn't graduate from Texas A&M University and will lead in education and will be on the cutting edge of what happens.
Now, just think about what that would mean to this institution and to education if that were to occur.
Then we become
the seed institution for educational reform for how many years to come?
And that's why I'm optimistic.
And I think that would be exciting for a faculty to begin to work with the high quality students that we have coming to us and follow them through into a professional career.
That's my view.
That's a very bright outlook.
And I think that should be appreciated.
And I hope that everybody would feel that way, because it is.
so important.
And I really appreciate your time and all of this very good insights because it's a totally different.
No, I really appreciate it.
And I hope that you let me come back and ask a few questions as I start to synthesize all of it.
I know I'll have to.
